{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656410"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.55,0.23,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77268"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77268"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECarbon dioxide transport in blood involves multiple mechanisms, including the formation of carbamino compounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of carbamino compounds in blood?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binding of carbon dioxide to carbonic anhydrase","Direct binding of carbon dioxide to protein amino groups","Formation of carbonic acid from carbon dioxide","Dissolution of carbon dioxide in plasma","Conversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate ions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect binding of carbon dioxide to protein amino groups\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes carbamino compound formation. Carbon dioxide reacts reversibly with the terminal amino groups of proteins, particularly haemoglobin, forming a carbamate group. This reaction is pH-dependent and accounts for approximately 5-10% of total carbon dioxide transport in blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate ions\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the primary mechanism of carbon dioxide transport (approximately 90%), but is distinct from carbamino formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissolution of carbon dioxide in plasma\u003C/strong\u003E - This accounts for only about 5% of carbon dioxide transport and does not involve chemical binding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding of carbon dioxide to carbonic anhydrase\u003C/strong\u003E - Carbonic anhydrase is an enzyme that catalyses the conversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate; it does not form carbamino compounds\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of carbonic acid from carbon dioxide\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an intermediate step in bicarbonate formation, not carbamino compound formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbon dioxide can bind directly to amino groups on proteins to form carbamino compounds, particularly with haemoglobin.","Carbamino compound formation is a reversible reaction that depends on pH and carbon dioxide concentration.","About 5-10% of total carbon dioxide transport in blood occurs via carbamino compounds."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:12:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:13:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77268"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships"